# Design Specification â€“ Column charts in the Roi Chart Library

## Introduction

This document describes the requirements to the roi chart library which is built to support the very specific requirements of the roiPE application for dashboarding. The chart library should be built as a generic chart library which can be used in JavaScript / HTML5 applications to render charts as SVG elements.

The recommended technology for this is D3, as it has proven itself as a highly flexible and customizable technology.

The target platforms for the charts rendered by this library are:

- IE 11 and later (IE 11 is the current Bayer standard browser)
- iPad
- Firefox 52 and later (secondary browser in the Bayer environment)

To enable maintainability the development of automated tests should be included in the development process. When a new feature is added, a test case for this new feature has to be built and will become part of the whole set of test cases.

## Supported chart types

As a starting point we want to support timeline charts, where the horizontal axis is a time axis or a category axis, and up to two vertical axises are supported for values.

An example chart based on this could look like this:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

The focus of the library should be:

- Performance â€“ performance target is that one chart renders in fewer than 100ms on a standard bayer laptop. The standard laptop right now is the Lenovo T470:
  - CPU: Intel Core i5-6300U 3.0G
  - RAM: 8GB DDR4 2133 SoDIMM
  - Graphics: Intel HD Graphics
  - HD: 256GB SSD PCIe-NVMe OPAL2
- Scalability â€“ when resizing the chart it should be responsive and charts should also perform with big data sets
- Flexibility â€“ it should be possible to easily extend charts and add new features

## Series types

The individual elements displayed in the chart should be called series. In the example above, there is a column series, a line series and a dashed line series.

The following series types are supported:

- Line series
  - Standard
  - Dashed
  - Undecorated
  - Forecast

- Column series
  - Standard columns
  - Bullet columns
  - Forecast columns
  - Inset columns
- Dot series
- Target series
- Candlesticks
- Area series
- Value range series
- Prognosis series

The meaning of the individual series types is explained in the document DS seriesTypes.docx.





## Series colors

The chart library allows for specification of the fill as well as the stroke of the series. The fill is the color that is used to fill areas, and the stroke is used for the outline. As an example in this area series, the fill is the lighter green and the stroke is the darker green on the edges of the fill:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

There are different ways to specify the colors, as they may also depend on the value that is shown. Here are the different possibilities offered by the chart library:

- ** Fixed color**

A specific color is selected for the series. The color will be used across all elements of the series. It is possible to specify the color as well as the alpha value. In the example above a fixed color is used for the fill and a different color is used for the stroke.

- ** Color based on value**

In some cases it makes sense to set the color based on the value that is the base for the series. One typical example is candle sticks, where e.g. negative values are shown in gray, and positive values are shown in red:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

The chart library allows for specification of three colors: the color to be used for positive values, the color to be used for negative values and the color to be used for neutral values. The neutral interval can be specified on the series level to determine when to use neutral color â€“ for example all values between -10 and +10 may fall into the neutral interval and thus use the neutral colors.

Additionally it is possible to specify that the value should be from a different data source â€“ by default the value of the actual series will be used for determining the color, but in some cases we may use the value of a different series for colorization.

- ** Color function**

There may be more advanced cases, like having different colorization logic per chart item. In this case the user can specify a color function, which will be called to determine the color of each individual chart item.



## Fill types

For any series that requires a fill, it is possible to specify the type of fill to be used. Three fill types are supported:

- ** Solid**

The area is filled with the specified color:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

- ** Cross hatched**

The area is filled with a cross hatched line pattern:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

- ** Outline**

The area is not filled, thus only the stroke is visible

## Group types

The chart library allows for grouping of series. Below you will see examples for the different group types, where two series with the same values are used across all examples. The following types of grouping are supported:

- ** Stacked**

The series are stacked on top of each other. The starting point of one series is the ending point of the previous series. In case of negative values the positive values and negative values are stacked separately.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

- ** Clustered**

The series are shown next to each other. The available space is distributed evenly across the series. Example:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

- ** Overlaid**

The series are drawn on top of each other. Example:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

- ** Overlapping**

The series partially overlap. Example:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Not all group types make sense for all series types. For example line series cannot be clustered.

## Data Labels

The chart library enables the display of data labels in the charts / for the individual series. In general all series types support data labels. However, if there is not enough space for displaying the data label, the chart library will automatically hide the data label.

The one exception here is that if there is only one series in the chart â€“ in this case the library will hide the chart item before hiding the data label.

Here is an example of this case in a bar chart:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)
  --- resize ---&gt; ![](data:image/*;base64,)

In column charts, it is possible to specify the desired rotation of the data labels. The default is that the data labels are drawn horizontally, but this may lead to overlapping labels, as shown in this example:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

If the label exceeds the width of the category, it will be automatically hidden.

The other aspect of data labels is where they are displayed. The following positions for data labels are supported:

- ** Centered**

The data label is drawn inside the chart item, e.g. inside the bar. For a column this means the label is drawn centered in the column. This makes sense e.g. when showing stacked columns:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

If the label is rotated and shown centered in a column chart, it could look like this:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

- ** Outside**

The data label is drawn on the outside, typically on top of the column (for negative values below the column).

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

        Again it may make sense to rotate the label in some cases:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Also when looking at series types with multiple values the data labels will look e.g. like this:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

## Dual vertical axises

The chart supports up to two vertical axises. Using two axises makes sense when showing information which is on a different scale, e.g. an absolute value and a percentage. The example shown at the very beginning has two vertical axises:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

One is showing data in days (the blue line and dashed black line are using this axis), the other is showing a number of line items, which is some orders of magnitude higher.

The axises are scaled based on the series assigned to it. If all series were shown on one axis, the blue and black lines would barely be visible as they are shown very close to 0.
